      <hedline>
        <hl1>Artistry in Brooklyn</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Gale Stevens Haynes, provost, Long Island University's Brooklyn campus, comments on Sept 28 article about encouraging cultural progress in downtown Brooklyn</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 28 news article about the encouraging cultural progress in downtown Brooklyn understates the potential of the arts there by not mentioning the roles that nearby campuses play as providers of audiences, performers and artists.</p>
        <p>Long Island University, along with other nearby educational institutions, is a member of the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Local Development Corporation, and thus part of the proposed cultural corridor.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 28 news article about the encouraging cultural progress in downtown Brooklyn understates the potential of the arts there by not mentioning the roles that nearby campuses play as providers of audiences, performers and artists.</p>
        <p>Long Island University, along with other nearby educational institutions, is a member of the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Local Development Corporation, and thus part of the proposed cultural corridor.</p>
        <p>The Brooklyn campus's recent renaissance, paralleling that of much of the surrounding downtown area, is a model of the ways the borough could put its special, pluralistic stamp on culture by drawing insight and strength from diversity.</p>
        <p>GALE STEVENS HAYNES  Brooklyn, Sept. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is provost of Long Island University's Brooklyn campus.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
